{"title_page": "Aso Villa", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox Historic building\n| name = Aso Rock Presidential Villa\n| owner = [[Federal Government of Nigeria]]\n| current_tenants = [[Muhammadu Buhari]], President of the [[Federal Republic of Nigeria]] and the First family.\n [[Yemi Osinbajo]], [[Vice President of the Federal Republic of Nigeria]] and family\n| location = Yakubu Gowon Crescent, [[Three Arms Zone|The Three Arms Zone]], [[Asokoro]], [[Abuja]], [[FCT, Nigeria|FCT]], Nigeria\n| website = {{URL|www.statehouse.gov.ng}}\n| coordinates = {{coord|9|3|25.6|N|7|31|29.2|E|display=inline,title}}\n| architect = \n| floor_area = <!-- {{convert|55000|sqft|abbr=on}} -->\n| client = \n| engineer = \n| start_date = {{Start date and age|1989|10|13}}\n| completion_date = {{Start date and age|1991|11|1}}\n| structural_system = \n| style = [[Neoclassical architecture|Neoclassical]], [[Palladian architecture|Palladian]]\n| size = \n}}\n'''Aso Villa''' (officially '''The Aso Rock Presidential Villa''') is the [[workplace]] and [[official residence]] of the [[President of Nigeria]] since 1991, when Nigeria moved its capital from [[Lagos]] to [[Abuja]]. It is located at Yakubu Gowon Crescent, [[Three_Arms_Zone|The Three Arms Zone]], Asokoro, Abuja, FCT, Nigeria. Several names that are used for Aso Villa include: '''State House''', '''The Rock''' and '''The Villa'''. The Aso Rock villa is the most protected presidential state house in Africa.<ref name=AbujaNews/><ref name=Buzz/>\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Secretary Tillerson Shakes Hands With Nigerian President Buhari (25901900897).jpg|thumb|left|President [[Muhammadu Buhari|Buhari]] meets with U.S. Secretary of State [[Rex Tillerson]] at the Presidential Villa, March 2018]]\nThe beautiful palatial residence was completed in 1991, the same year the military junta of [[Ibrahim Babangida]] relocated the national capital from [[Lagos]] to [[Abuja]]. Aso Villa encompasses the 400 meter monolith [[Aso Rock]], located within the [[Three Arms Zone]] of Abuja metropolis. In 1976 the Military Government of [[Murtala Mohammed]] took the decision to relocate the Federal Capital from Lagos by a committee under the leadership of Justice Akinola Aguda which recommended the creation of a Federal Capital Territory (FCT) in the center of the country and its proclamation to this effect  was issued on February 3, 1976. <ref>{{cite web|last1=The State House|title=The Villa|url=http://statehouse.gov.ng/the-villa/|website=Aso Rock Villa|accessdate=4 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504100746/http://statehouse.gov.ng/the-villa/|archive-date=4 May 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAkinola Aguda House (formally named on October 1, 1983) was originally conceived as a Presidential Lodge & Guest House Complex and hosted the first ever formal Cabinet Meeting held outside Lagos, only days after Abuja hosted Nigeria's Independence Anniversary celebrations for the first time, in October 1982. President Ibrahim Babangida, who took office in 1985, commenced construction of a new Presidential residence and in 1991 the Aso Rock Presidential Villa was completed and President Babangida became the first Head of State to occupy it, in on December 12, 1991. Upon completion of the Aso Rock Presidential Villa the Aguda House became the Vice Presidential Complex, and has remained so till date \u2014 apart from the period between 1999 and 2007 when the Vice President lived in a Residence that has since been transferred to the Judiciary as Official Quarters for the Chief Justice of Nigeria. <ref>{{cite web|last1=The State House|title=The Villa|url=http://statehouse.gov.ng/the-villa/|website=Aso Rock Villa|accessdate=4 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504100746/http://statehouse.gov.ng/the-villa/|archive-date=4 May 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, construction of a new Vice Presidential Residence commenced. The Residence has yet to be completed the [[Muhammadu Buhari|Buhari]] administration has said it is not a priority. Today the Presidential Complex, located in the Three Arms Zone of the Federal Capital Territory, consists of the Main Presidential Villa (Office and Residence of the President, and Offices of the Vice President and Wife of the President), the State House Conference Center, State House Annexe, and the Akinola Aguda House. The old [[Presidential Lodge]] in Marina, Lagos, was handed over to the Lagos State Government in 2017. <ref>{{cite web|last1=The State House|title=The Villa|url=http://statehouse.gov.ng/the-villa/|website=Aso Rock Villa|accessdate=4 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504100746/http://statehouse.gov.ng/the-villa/|archive-date=4 May 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe villa is currently under the protection of the [[Presidential Guard Brigade (Nigeria)|Presidential Guard Brigade]] which perform ceremonial and protective duties for the president. The brigade performs [[public duties]] in a weekly [[changing of the guard]] ceremony outside the villa.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=AbujaNews>{{cite web |url=http://www.abuja-ng.com/aso-rock.html |title=Aso Rock Presidential Villa |work=Abuja News |accessdate=March 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Buzz>{{cite web |url=http://buzznigeria.com/inside-photos-aso-rock-presidential-villa-will-make-salivate/ |title=11 Rare Inside Photos and Videos of Aso Rock Presidential Villa |work=Buzz Nigeria |accessdate=March 3, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n\n{{Presidential Palaces in Africa}}\n{{Abuja}}\n\n[[Category:Presidential residences]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Abuja]]\n[[Category:Official residences in Nigeria]]\n\n{{nigeria-struct-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox Historic building\n| name                = Aso Rock Presidential Villa\n| owner               = [[Federal Government of Nigeria]]\n| current_tenants     = [[Muhammadu Buhari]], President of the [[Federal Republic of Nigeria]] and the First family\n| location            = Yakubu Gowon Crescent, [[Three Arms Zone|The Three Arms Zone]], [[Asokoro]], [[Abuja]], [[FCT, Nigeria|FCT]], Nigeria\n| website =  {{URL|www.statehouse.gov.ng}}\n| coordinates         = {{coord|9|3|25.6|N|7|31|29.2|E|display=inline,title}}\n| architect =\n| floor_area = <!-- {{convert|55000|sqft|abbr=on}} -->\n| client =\n| engineer =\n| start_date = {{Start date and age|1989|10|13}}\n| completion_date = {{Start date and age|1991|11|1}}\n| structural_system =\n| style = [[Neoclassical architecture|Neoclassical]], [[Palladian architecture|Palladian]]\n| size =\n}}\n'''Aso Villa''' (officially '''The Aso Rock Presidential Villa''') is the [[workplace]] and [[official residence]] of the [[President of Nigeria]] since 1991, when Nigeria moved its capital from [[Lagos]] to [[Abuja]]. It is located at Yakubu Gowon Crescent, [[Three_Arms_Zone|The Three Arms Zone]], Asokoro, Abuja, FCT, Nigeria. Several names that are used for Aso Villa include: '''State House''', '''The Rock''' and '''The Villa'''. The Aso Rock villa is the most protected presidential state house in Africa.<ref name=AbujaNews/><ref name=Buzz/>\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Secretary Tillerson Shakes Hands With Nigerian President Buhari (25901900897).jpg|thumb|left|President [[Muhammadu Buhari|Buhari]] meets with U.S. Secretary of State [[Rex Tillerson]] at the Presidential Villa, March 2018]]\nThe beautiful palatial residence was completed in 1991, the same year the military junta of [[Ibrahim Babangida]] relocated the national capital from [[Lagos]] to [[Abuja]]. Aso Villa encompasses the 400 meter monolith [[Aso Rock]], located within the [[Three Arms Zone]] of Abuja metropolis. In 1976 the Military Government of [[Murtala Mohammed]] took the decision to relocate the Federal Capital from Lagos by a committee under the leadership of Justice Akinola Aguda which recommended the creation of a Federal Capital Territory (FCT) in the center of the country and its proclamation to this effect  was issued on February 3, 1976. <ref>{{cite web|last1=The State House|title=The Villa|url=http://statehouse.gov.ng/the-villa/|website=Aso Rock Villa|accessdate=4 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504100746/http://statehouse.gov.ng/the-villa/|archive-date=4 May 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAkinola Aguda House (formally named on October 1, 1983) was originally conceived as a Presidential Lodge & Guest House Complex and hosted the first ever formal Cabinet Meeting held outside Lagos, only days after Abuja hosted Nigeria's Independence Anniversary celebrations for the first time, in October 1982. President Ibrahim Babangida, who took office in 1985, commenced construction of a new Presidential residence and in 1991 the Aso Rock Presidential Villa was completed and President Babangida became the first Head of State to occupy it, in on December 12, 1991. Upon completion of the Aso Rock Presidential Villa the Aguda House became the Vice Presidential Complex, and has remained so till date \u2014 apart from the period between 1999 and 2007 when the Vice President lived in a Residence that has since been transferred to the Judiciary as Official Quarters for the Chief Justice of Nigeria. <ref>{{cite web|last1=The State House|title=The Villa|url=http://statehouse.gov.ng/the-villa/|website=Aso Rock Villa|accessdate=4 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504100746/http://statehouse.gov.ng/the-villa/|archive-date=4 May 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, construction of a new Vice Presidential Residence commenced. The Residence has yet to be completed the [[Muhammadu Buhari|Buhari]] administration has said it is not a priority. Today the Presidential Complex, located in the Three Arms Zone of the Federal Capital Territory, consists of the Main Presidential Villa (Office and Residence of the President, and Offices of the Vice President and Wife of the President), the State House Conference Center, State House Annexe, and the Akinola Aguda House. The old [[Presidential Lodge]] in Marina, Lagos, was handed over to the Lagos State Government in 2017. <ref>{{cite web|last1=The State House|title=The Villa|url=http://statehouse.gov.ng/the-villa/|website=Aso Rock Villa|accessdate=4 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504100746/http://statehouse.gov.ng/the-villa/|archive-date=4 May 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe villa is currently under the protection of the [[Presidential Guard Brigade (Nigeria)|Presidential Guard Brigade]] which perform ceremonial and protective duties for the president. The brigade performs [[public duties]] in a weekly [[changing of the guard]] ceremony outside the villa.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=AbujaNews>{{cite web |url=http://www.abuja-ng.com/aso-rock.html |title=Aso Rock Presidential Villa |work=Abuja News |accessdate=March 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Buzz>{{cite web |url=http://buzznigeria.com/inside-photos-aso-rock-presidential-villa-will-make-salivate/ |title=11 Rare Inside Photos and Videos of Aso Rock Presidential Villa |work=Buzz Nigeria |accessdate=March 3, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n\n{{Presidential Palaces in Africa}}\n{{Abuja}}\n\n[[Category:Presidential residences]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Abuja]]\n[[Category:Official residences in Nigeria]]\n\n{{nigeria-struct-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Menneth", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aso_Villa"}
{"title_page": "Arthritis mutilans", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical condition\n| name            = Arthritis mutilans\n| synonyms        = \n| image           = Reumatoidalne zapalenie stawow 01.jpg\n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| synonym         = \n| pronounce       = \n| field           = \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Arthritis mutilans''' is a rare medical condition involving severe inflammation damaging the joints of the hands and feet, and resulting in deformation and problems with moving the affected areas; it can also affect the spine.<ref>[[National Institutes of Health]] Genetics Home Reference, [https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/condition/psoriatic-arthritis Psoriatic arthritis]. Accessed 2016-11-06.</ref> As an uncommon [[arthropathy]], arthritis mutilans was originally described as affecting the hands, feet, fingers, and/or toes, but can refer in general to severe derangement of any joint damaged by arthropathy.<ref name=\"Nielsen\">{{cite journal | author = Nielsen B\u00f8rge, Snorrason Egill | year = 1946 | title = Arthritis mutilans | url = http://acr.sagepub.com/content/os-27/6.toc | journal = [[Acta Radiologica]] | volume = 27 | issue = | pages = 607\u2013616 | doi = 10.1177/028418514602700605 }}</ref> First described in modern medical literature by Marie and Leri in 1913, in the hands, arthritis mutilans is also known as '''opera glass hand''' (''la main en lorgnette'' in French), or '''chronic absorptive arthritis'''.<ref name=\"Nelson\">Nelson, L. S., [http://jbjs.org/content/20/4/1045 The Opera-Glass Hand in Chronic Arthritis. \"La Main en Lorgnette\" of Marie and Leri] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161107163551/http://jbjs.org/content/20/4/1045 |date=2016-11-07 }}, ''[[Journal of Bone and Joint Surgery]]'', 20:1045-1049, 1938-10-1. Accessed 2016-11-6. [https://web.archive.org/web/20140414075126/http://jbjs.org/article.aspx?articleid=9167 Archived version] at archive.org.</ref><ref name=\"pmid14783359\">{{cite journal | pmid = 14783359 | volume=9 | title=Chronic absorptive arthritis or opera-glass hand: report of 8 cases | pmc=1030771 | date=September 1950 | author=Solomon WM, Stecher RM | journal=Ann. Rheum. Dis. | pages=209\u201320 }}</ref> Sometimes there is foot involvement in which toes shorten and on which painful calluses develop in a condition known as opera glass foot, or ''pied en lorgnette''.<ref name=\"Froimson\">{{cite journal | pmid = 4939959 | volume=53 | issue=7 | title=Hand reconstruction in arthritis mutilans. A case report | date=October 1971 | author=Froimson AI | journal=J Bone Joint Surg Am | pages=1377\u201382 }}</ref><ref name=\"Eisenstadt\">{{cite journal | url = http://jbjs.org/content/37/2/337.long | pmid = 14367425 | volume=37-A | title=Arthritis mutilans (doigt, main, pied enlorgnette) | date=April 1955 | author=Eisenstadt HB, Eggers GW | journal=J Bone Joint Surg Am | pages=337\u201346 }}</ref>\n\n== Signs and symptoms ==\nFor a person with arthritis mutilans in the hands, the fingers become shortened by [[arthritis]], and the shortening may become severe enough that the hand looks paw-like, with the first deformity occurring at the [[interphalangeal articulations of hand|interphalangeal]] and [[metacarpophalangeal joint]]s. The excess skin from the shortening of the [[phalanx bone]]s becomes folded transversely, as if retracted into one another like [[opera glasses]], hence the description ''la main en lorgnette''. As the condition worsens, [[Joint dislocation|luxation]], phalangeal and [[metacarpus|metacarpal]] bone absorption, and skeletal architecture loss in the fingers occurs.<ref name=\"Froimson\" />\n\n== Cause ==\nArthritis mutilans occurs mainly in people who have pre-existing [[psoriatic arthritis]], but can occur, if less often, in advanced rheumatoid arthritis; it can also occur independently.<ref name=\"Froimson\" /><ref name=\"Eisenstadt\" /> Psoriasis and psoriatic arthritis are interrelated heritable diseases, occurring with greater heritable frequency than [[rheumatoid arthritis]], primary [[Sj\u00f6gren syndrome]] and thyroid disease.<ref name=\"Nograles\">Nograles, K., Brasington, R. and Bowcock, A., \"New insights into the pathogenesis and genetics of psoriatic arthritis, ''Nature clinical practice. Rheumatology'', 5(2):83\u201391  {{doi|10.1038/ncprheum0987}}</ref> Psoriasis affects 2\u20133% of the Caucasian population, and psoriatic arthritis affects up to 30% of those.<ref name=\"Nograles\" /> Arthritis mutilans presents in about 5\u201316% of psoriatic arthritis cases, involves [[osteolysis]] of the [[distal interphalangeal joint|DIP]] and [[interphalangeal joints of the hand|PIP]] joints, and can include bone [[edema]], [[bone erosion]]s, and new bone growth.<ref name=\"Matuszewska\">Sudo\u0142-Szopi\u0144ska I., Matuszewska G., Kwiatkowska B., Praco\u0144 G., \"Diagnostic imaging of psoriatic arthritis. Part I: etiopathogenesis, classifications and radiographic features, ''Journal of Ultrasonography'', 16(64):65\u201377 {{doi|10.15557/JoU.2016.0007}}</ref> Most often psoriatic arthritis is [[serostatus|seronegative]] for [[rheumatoid factor]] (occurring in only about 13% of cases<ref name=\"Rodgers\">Rodgers M., Epstein D., Bojke L., et al, [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK109507/ Etanercept, Infliximab and Adalimumab for the Treatment of Psoriatic Arthritis: A Systematic Review and Economic Evaluation], ''Health Technology Assessment'', 15.10,  Feb.   p.1. </ref>), and has genetic risk factor overlap with [[ankylosing spondylitis]] with [[HLA-B27]], [[interleukin-23 receptor|IL-23R77]], and [[interleukin-1 family|IL-1]],<ref name=\"Nograles\" /> however, as of 2016, [[pathogenesis|immunopathogenesis]] is unclear.<ref name=\"Matuszewska\" />\n\n== Diagnosis ==\n[[Enthesitis]] can assist in differentiating arthritis mutilans' parent condition psoriatic arthritis from rheumatoid arthritis and [[osteoarthritis]], with evidence in plain radiographs (x-rays) and [[Magnetic resonance imaging|MRI]] as [[periostitis]], new bone formation, and bone erosions.<ref name=\"Nograles\" /> [[Dactylitis]], [[spondylitis]] and [[sacroiliitis]] are common with the parent condition psoriatic arthritis, but are not in rheumatoid arthritis.<ref name=\"Rodgers\" /> MRI bone edema scores are high in arthritis mutilans and correlate with radiographic measures of joint damage, although they may not correlate with disease activity.<ref name=\"YMAl2015\">{{cite journal | pmid = 19126234 | doi=10.1186/ar2586 | volume=11 | title=MRI bone oedema scores are higher in the arthritis mutilans form of psoriatic arthritis and correlate with high radiographic scores for joint damage | pmc=2688232 | year=2009 | journal=Arthritis Res. Ther. | page=R2 | author=Tan YM, \u00d8stergaard M, Doyle A, Dalbeth N, Lobo M, Reeves Q, Robinson E, Taylor WJ, Jones PB, Pui K, Lee J, McQueen FM }}. Report of a study investigating MRI features of bone disease in arthritis mutilans as a form of psoriatic arthritis.</ref> A source of significant pain, bone marrow edema (or lesions, using newer terminology), can be detected on MRI or with ultrasonography by signals of excessive water in bone marrow.<ref name=\"Eriksen\">{{cite journal | author = Eriksen E | year = 2015| title = Treatment of bone marrow lesions (bone marrow edema) | url = | journal = BoneKEy Reports | volume = 4 | issue = | page = 755 | doi = 10.1038/bonekey.2015.124 }}</ref> Specifically, bone marrow edema can be detected within bone on [[Spin\u2013lattice relaxation#T1 weighted images|T1-weighted]] images as poorly defined areas of low signal, with a high signal on [[magnetic resonance imaging#T2-weighted MRI|T2-weighted]] fat-suppressed images.<ref>{{cite journal | author = McQueen F.M., Benton N., Perry D., Crabbe J. | display-authors = etal | year = 2003| title = , Bone edema scored on magnetic resonance imaging scans of the dominant carpus at presentation predicts radiographic joint damage of the hands and feet six years later in patients with rheumatoid arthritis | url = | journal = Arthritis and Rheumatology | volume = 48 | issue = 7| pages = 1814\u20131827 | doi = 10.1002/art.11162 }}</ref> Comparatively, with arthritis mutilans in ''rheumatoid arthritis'', bone marrow edema often involves the [[Wikt:subchondral|subchondral]] bone layer, while the condition as a subtype of ''psoriatic arthritis'' includes a greater extent of marrow edema, expanding to [[diaphysis]].<ref name=\"YMAl2015\" /><ref name=\"Pracon\">{{cite journal | author = Sudo\u0142-Szopi\u0144ska I., Praco\u0144 G. | year = 2016| title = Diagnostic imaging of psoriatic arthritis. Part II: magnetic resonance imaging and ultrasonography | url = | journal = Journal of Ultrasonography | volume = 16 | issue = 65| pages = 163\u2013174 | doi = 10.15557/JoU.2016.0018 }}</ref>\n\n== Treatment ==\n=== Medication ===\nThe bone edema in arthritis mutilans can be treated with [[TNF inhibitor]]s in the short term: a 2007 study found that the bone edema associated with psoriatic arthritis (of which arthritis mutilans is a subtype) responded to TNF inhibitors with \"dramatic\" improvement, but the study was not determinative of whether TNF inhibitors would prevent new bone formation, bone fusion, or osteolysis ([[bone resorption]]).<ref name=\"YMAl2015\" /><ref name=\"Ortega\">{{cite journal | author = Marzo-Ortega H., McGonagle D. | display-authors = etal | year = 2007| title = , Efficacy of infliximab on MRI\u2010determined bone oedema in psoriatic arthritis | journal = Annals of the Rheumatic Diseases | volume = 66 | issue = 6| pages = 778\u2013781 | doi = 10.1136/ard.2006.063818 | pmid = 17185324 | pmc = 1954680 }}</ref>\n\n=== Surgical ===\nAlthough a 2011 research article stated that disagreements between hand surgeons and rheumatologists remain regarding the indications, timing and effectiveness of rheumatoid hand surgery,<ref name=\"pmid21463736\">{{cite journal | author = Chung Kevin C., Pushman Allison G. | year = 2011 | title = Current Concepts in the Management of the Rheumatoid Hand | url = http://www.jhandsurg.org/article/S0363-5023%2811%2900090-6/abstract | journal = Journal of Hand Surgery | volume = 36 | issue = 4| pages = 736\u2013747 | doi = 10.1016/j.jhsa.2011.01.019 | pmid = 21463736 | pmc = 3086569 }}</ref> arthritis mutilans may be successfully treated by [[Ilium (bone)|iliac]]-[[bone grafting|bone graft]] and [[arthrodesis]] of the interphalangeal joints and the metacarpophalangeal joint in each finger.<ref name=\"Froimson\" /><ref name=\"pmid 1018089\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Nalebuff EA, Garrett J |title=Opera-glass hand in rheumatoid arthritis |journal=J Hand Surg Am |volume=1 |issue=3 |pages=210\u201320 |year=1976 |pmid=1018089 |doi= 10.1016/s0363-5023(76)80040-8|url=}}</ref>\n\n== Outcomes ==\nArthritis mutilans' parent condition psoriatic arthritis leaves people with a mortality risk 60% higher than the general population, with premature death causes mirroring those of the general population, cardiovascular issues being most common.<ref name=\"Rodgers\" /><ref name=\"Gladman\">Gladman DD, Antoni C, Mease P, Clegg DO, Nash P.,  2005 \"Psoriatic arthritis: epidemiology, clinical features, course, and outcome ''Annals of the Rheumatic Diseases'', 64(Suppl 2):ii14\u2013ii17. {{doi|10.1136/ard.2004.032482}}</ref> Life expectancy for people with psoriatic arthritis is estimated to be reduced by approximately 3 years.<ref name=\"Rodgers\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|  ICD10           = {{ICD10|M07.1}}\n|  ICD9            = {{ICD9|696}}\n|  ICDO            =\n|  OMIM            =\n|  DiseasesDB      = C0702102\n|  MedlinePlus     =\n|  eMedicineSubj   =\n|  eMedicineTopic  =\n|  MeSH            =\n|  GeneReviewsNBK  =\n|  GeneReviewsName =\n|  Orphanet        =\n}}\n{{Arthropathies and related conditions}}\n{{Spinal disease}}\n\n{{Medicine}}\n\n[[Category:Rheumatology]]\n[[Category:Arthritis]]\n[[Category:Autoimmune diseases]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical condition\n| name            = Arthritis mutilans\n| synonyms        = \n| image           = Reumatoidalne zapalenie stawow 01.jpg\n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| synonym         = \n| pronounce       = \n| field           = \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Arthritis mutilans''' is a rare medical condition involving severe inflammation damaging the joints of the hands and feet, and resulting in deformation and problems with moving the affected areas; it can also affect the spine.<ref>[[National Institutes of Health]] Genetics Home Reference, [https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/condition/psoriatic-arthritis Psoriatic arthritis]. Accessed 2016-11-06.</ref> As an uncommon [[arthropathy]], arthritis mutilans was originally described as affecting the hands, feet, fingers, and/or toes, but can refer in general to severe derangement of any joint damaged by arthropathy.<ref name=\"Nielsen\">Nielsen, B\u00f8rge, and Egill Snorrason [http://acr.sagepub.com/content/os-27/6.toc Arthritis mutilans], ''[[Acta Radiologica]]''  1946; 27: 607-616, {{DOI|10.1177/028418514602700605}}</ref> First described in modern medical literature by Marie and Leri in 1913, in the hands, arthritis mutilans is also known as '''opera glass hand''' (''la main en lorgnette'' in French), or '''chronic absorptive arthritis'''.<ref name=\"Nelson\">Nelson, L. S., [http://jbjs.org/content/20/4/1045 The Opera-Glass Hand in Chronic Arthritis. \"La Main en Lorgnette\" of Marie and Leri] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161107163551/http://jbjs.org/content/20/4/1045 |date=2016-11-07 }}, ''[[Journal of Bone and Joint Surgery]]'', 20:1045-1049, 1938-10-1. Accessed 2016-11-6. [https://web.archive.org/web/20140414075126/http://jbjs.org/article.aspx?articleid=9167 Archived version] at archive.org.</ref><ref name=\"pmid14783359\">Solomon, W.M., Stecher, R.M.,  \"Chronic Absorptive Arthritis or Opera-Glass Hand: report of 8 cases, ''[[Annals of the Rheumatic Diseases]]'', 1950; 9(3):209\u2013220, PMID 14783359.  </ref> Sometimes there is foot involvement in which toes shorten and on which painful calluses develop in a condition known as opera glass foot, or ''pied en lorgnette''.<ref name=\"Froimson\">{{cite journal | pmid = 4939959 | volume=53 | issue=7 | title=Hand reconstruction in arthritis mutilans. A case report | date=October 1971 | author=Froimson AI | journal=J Bone Joint Surg Am | pages=1377\u201382 }}</ref><ref name=\"Eisenstadt\">Eisenstadt, H. B., and Eggers, G.W.N., [http://jbjs.org/content/37/2/337.long Arthritis Mutilans]  ''Journal of Bone and Joint Surgery'', 37-A:337-346 PMID 14367425. </ref>\n\n== Signs and symptoms ==\nFor a person with arthritis mutilans in the hands, the fingers become shortened by [[arthritis]], and the shortening may become severe enough that the hand looks paw-like, with the first deformity occurring at the [[interphalangeal articulations of hand|interphalangeal]] and [[metacarpophalangeal joint]]s. The excess skin from the shortening of the [[phalanx bone]]s becomes folded transversely, as if retracted into one another like [[opera glasses]], hence the description ''la main en lorgnette''. As the condition worsens, [[Joint dislocation|luxation]], phalangeal and [[metacarpus|metacarpal]] bone absorption, and skeletal architecture loss in the fingers occurs.<ref name=\"Froimson\" />\n\n== Cause ==\nArthritis mutilans occurs mainly in people who have pre-existing [[psoriatic arthritis]], but can occur, if less often, in advanced rheumatoid arthritis; it can also occur independently.<ref name=\"Froimson\" /><ref name=\"Eisenstadt\" /> Psoriasis and psoriatic arthritis are interrelated heritable diseases, occurring with greater heritable frequency than [[rheumatoid arthritis]], primary [[Sj\u00f6gren syndrome]] and thyroid disease.<ref name=\"Nograles\">Nograles, K., Brasington, R. and Bowcock, A., New insights into the pathogenesis and genetics of psoriatic arthritis, ''Nature clinical practice. Rheumatology'', 5(2):83\u201391,  {{doi|10.1038/ncprheum0987}}</ref> Psoriasis affects 2\u20133% of the Caucasian population, and psoriatic arthritis affects up to 30% of those.<ref name=\"Nograles\" /> Arthritis mutilans presents in about 5\u201316% of psoriatic arthritis cases, involves [[osteolysis]] of the [[distal interphalangeal joint|DIP]] and [[interphalangeal joints of the hand|PIP]] joints, and can include bone [[edema]], [[bone erosion]]s, and new bone growth.<ref name=\"Matuszewska\">Sudo\u0142-Szopi\u0144ska I., Matuszewska G., Kwiatkowska B., Praco\u0144 G., Diagnostic imaging of psoriatic arthritis. Part I: etiopathogenesis, classifications and radiographic features, ''Journal of Ultrasonography'', 16(64):65\u201377 {{doi|10.15557/JoU.2016.0007}} </ref> Most often psoriatic arthritis is [[serostatus|seronegative]] for [[rheumatoid factor]] (occurring in only about 13% of cases<ref name=\"Rodgers\">Rodgers M., Epstein D., Bojke L., et al, [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK109507/ Etanercept, Infliximab and Adalimumab for the Treatment of Psoriatic Arthritis: A Systematic Review and Economic Evaluation], ''Health Technology Assessment'', No. 15.10, Southampton (UK): NIHR Journals Library, Feb. 2011, p.1. Accessed 2016-11-06.</ref>), and has genetic risk factor overlap with [[ankylosing spondylitis]] with [[HLA-B27]], [[interleukin-23 receptor|IL-23R77]], and [[interleukin-1 family|IL-1]],<ref name=\"Nograles\" /> however, as of 2016, [[pathogenesis|immunopathogenesis]] is unclear.<ref name=\"Matuszewska\" />\n\n== Diagnosis ==\n[[Enthesitis]] can assist in differentiating arthritis mutilans' parent condition psoriatic arthritis from rheumatoid arthritis and [[osteoarthritis]], with evidence in plain radiographs (x-rays) and [[Magnetic resonance imaging|MRI]] as [[periostitis]], new bone formation, and bone erosions.<ref name=\"Nograles\" /> [[Dactylitis]], [[spondylitis]] and [[sacroiliitis]] are common with the parent condition psoriatic arthritis, but are not in rheumatoid arthritis.<ref name=\"Rodgers\" /> MRI bone edema scores are high in arthritis mutilans and correlate with radiographic measures of joint damage, although they may not correlate with disease activity.<ref name=\"YMAl2015\">{{cite journal | pmid = 19126234 | doi=10.1186/ar2586 | volume=11 | title=MRI bone oedema scores are higher in the arthritis mutilans form of psoriatic arthritis and correlate with high radiographic scores for joint damage | pmc=2688232 | year=2009 | journal=Arthritis Res. Ther. | page=R2 | author=Tan YM, \u00d8stergaard M, Doyle A, Dalbeth N, Lobo M, Reeves Q, Robinson E, Taylor WJ, Jones PB, Pui K, Lee J, McQueen FM }}. Report of a study investigating MRI features of bone disease in arthritis mutilans as a form of psoriatic arthritis.</ref> A source of significant pain, bone marrow edema (or lesions, using newer terminology), can be detected on MRI or with ultrasonography by signals of excessive water in bone marrow.<ref name=\"Eriksen\">{{cite journal | author = Eriksen E | year = 2015| title = Treatment of bone marrow lesions (bone marrow edema) | url = | journal = BoneKEy Reports | volume = 4 | issue = | page = 755 | doi = 10.1038/bonekey.2015.124 }}</ref> Specifically, bone marrow edema can be detected within bone on [[Spin\u2013lattice relaxation#T1 weighted images|T1-weighted]] images as poorly defined areas of low signal, with a high signal on [[magnetic resonance imaging#T2-weighted MRI|T2-weighted]] fat-suppressed images.<ref>{{cite journal | author = McQueen F.M., Benton N., Perry D., Crabbe J. | display-authors = etal | year = 2003| title = , Bone edema scored on magnetic resonance imaging scans of the dominant carpus at presentation predicts radiographic joint damage of the hands and feet six years later in patients with rheumatoid arthritis | url = | journal = Arthritis and Rheumatology | volume = 48 | issue = 7| pages = 1814\u20131827 | doi = 10.1002/art.11162 }}</ref> Comparatively, with arthritis mutilans in ''rheumatoid arthritis'', bone marrow edema often involves the [[Wikt:subchondral|subchondral]] bone layer, while the condition as a subtype of ''psoriatic arthritis'' includes a greater extent of marrow edema, expanding to [[diaphysis]].<ref name=\"YMAl2015\" /><ref name=\"Pracon\">{{cite journal | author = Sudo\u0142-Szopi\u0144ska I., Praco\u0144 G. | year = 2016| title = Diagnostic imaging of psoriatic arthritis. Part II: magnetic resonance imaging and ultrasonography | url = | journal = Journal of Ultrasonography | volume = 16 | issue = 65| pages = 163\u2013174 | doi = 10.15557/JoU.2016.0018 }}</ref>\n\n== Treatment ==\n=== Medication ===\nThe bone edema in arthritis mutilans can be treated with [[TNF inhibitor]]s in the short term: a 2007 study found that the bone edema associated with psoriatic arthritis (of which arthritis mutilans is a subtype) responded to TNF inhibitors with \"dramatic\" improvement, but the study was not determinative of whether TNF inhibitors would prevent new bone formation, bone fusion, or osteolysis ([[bone resorption]]).<ref name=\"YMAl2015\" /><ref name=\"Ortega\">{{cite journal | author = Marzo-Ortega H., McGonagle D. | display-authors = etal | year = 2007| title = , Efficacy of infliximab on MRI\u2010determined bone oedema in psoriatic arthritis | journal = Annals of the Rheumatic Diseases | volume = 66 | issue = 6| pages = 778\u2013781 | doi = 10.1136/ard.2006.063818 | pmid = 17185324 | pmc = 1954680 }}</ref>\n\n=== Surgical ===\nAlthough a 2011 research article stated that disagreements between hand surgeons and rheumatologists remain regarding the indications, timing and effectiveness of rheumatoid hand surgery,<ref name=\"pmid21463736\">{{cite journal | author = Chung Kevin C., Pushman Allison G. | year = 2011 | title = Current Concepts in the Management of the Rheumatoid Hand | url = http://www.jhandsurg.org/article/S0363-5023%2811%2900090-6/abstract | journal = Journal of Hand Surgery | volume = 36 | issue = 4| pages = 736\u2013747 | doi = 10.1016/j.jhsa.2011.01.019 | pmid = 21463736 | pmc = 3086569 }}</ref> arthritis mutilans may be successfully treated by [[Ilium (bone)|iliac]]-[[bone grafting|bone graft]] and [[arthrodesis]] of the interphalangeal joints and the metacarpophalangeal joint in each finger.<ref name=\"Froimson\" /><ref name=\"pmid 1018089\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Nalebuff EA, Garrett J |title=Opera-glass hand in rheumatoid arthritis |journal=J Hand Surg Am |volume=1 |issue=3 |pages=210\u201320 |year=1976 |pmid=1018089 |doi= 10.1016/s0363-5023(76)80040-8|url=}}</ref>\n\n== Outcomes ==\nArthritis mutilans' parent condition psoriatic arthritis leaves people with a mortality risk 60% higher than the general population, with premature death causes mirroring those of the general population, cardiovascular issues being most common.<ref name=\"Rodgers\" /><ref name=\"Gladman\">Gladman DD, Antoni C, Mease P, Clegg DO, Nash P., Psoriatic arthritis: epidemiology, clinical features, course, and outcome],'' Annals of the Rheumatic Diseases'', 64(Suppl 2):ii14\u2013ii17, Mar. 2005. {{doi|10.1136/ard.2004.032482}}, {{PMC|1766874}}.</ref> Life expectancy for people with psoriatic arthritis is estimated to be reduced by approximately 3 years.<ref name=\"Rodgers\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|  ICD10           = {{ICD10|M07.1}}\n|  ICD9            = {{ICD9|696}}\n|  ICDO            =\n|  OMIM            =\n|  DiseasesDB      = C0702102\n|  MedlinePlus     =\n|  eMedicineSubj   =\n|  eMedicineTopic  =\n|  MeSH            =\n|  GeneReviewsNBK  =\n|  GeneReviewsName =\n|  Orphanet        =\n}}\n{{Arthropathies and related conditions}}\n{{Spinal disease}}\n\n{{Medicine}}\n\n[[Category:Rheumatology]]\n[[Category:Arthritis]]\n[[Category:Autoimmune diseases]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:, added 1 PMC, templated 1 journal cites (Diberri fmt authors)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arthritis_mutilans"}
{"title_page": "Continuum (sculpture)", "text_new": "{{Infobox artwork\n| image_file = Smithsonian Air and Space.jpg\n| painting_alignment = Front\n| image_size         = 200px\n| title              = Continuum\n| alt                =\n| other_language_1   =\n| other_title_1      =\n| other_language_2   =\n| other_title_2      =\n| artist             = Charles O. Perry\n| year               = {{Start date|1976}}\n| type               = [[Bronze]]\n| height_metric      =\n| width_metric       =\n| length_metric      =\n| height_imperial    = 14\n| width_imperial     =\n| length_imperial    =\n| metric_unit        = m\n| imperial_unit      = ft\n| city               = [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]]\n| museum             = [[National Air and Space Museum]]\n| coordinates        = {{coord|38|53|15.93|N|77|1|11.6|W|region:US}}\n| owner              = [[Smithsonian Institution]]\n}}\n\n'''''Continuum''''' is a public artwork by [[United States|American]] sculptor [[Charles O. Perry]]  located in front of the [[National Air and Space Museum]] in [[Washington, DC]], [[United States]].<ref name=\"Continuum\">{{cite web | author=Smithsonian | year=1993 | title=Continuum, (sculpture). | work=Save Outdoor Sculpture | publisher=Smithsonian | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!6509~!0#focus | accessdate= 2 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n\nThe sculpture is a large swirling abstract that consists of 8 bronze pieces painted black and placed on a pole. It moves freely.<ref name=\"Continuum\"/>\n\n==Information==\nAccording to the artist the piece \"began as an exploration of the [[M\u00f6bius strip]], a product of pure mathematics formed by joining two ends of a strip of paper after giving one end a 180 degree twist, thus creating only one edge. The center of the bronze sculpture symbolizes a [[black hole]], while the edge shows the flow of matter through the center from positive to negative space and back again in a [[continuum (theory)|continuum]].\"<ref name=\"CharlesOPerry\">{{cite web | author=Charles O. Perry | year= | title=Biography | work= | publisher=Charles Perry | url=http://www.charlesperry.com/Bio.html | accessdate= 2 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nA similar sculpture by Perry, ''Continuum II'', is installed in [[Marina Square]] in [[Singapore]] and dates to 1986.<ref name=\"Continuum II\">{{cite web | title=Continuum II | work=Singapore Public Art | publisher=Singapore Public Art | url=http://www.publicart.sg/?q=Charles-O-Perry_Continuum-II | accessdate=2 January 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619070004/http://www.publicart.sg/?q=Charles-O-Perry_Continuum-II | archive-date=19 June 2010 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n<gallery mode=packed heights=200>\nFile:Continuum from below.JPG|from below\nFile:Continuum from front (S).JPG|from the front (S)\nFile:Continuum from back (N) 05.JPG|from the side (SW)\nFile:Continuum from NW.JPG|from the side (NW)\nFile:Continuum from back (N).JPG|from the back (N)\nFile:Continuum Conservation.jpg|undergoing conservation in 2010\n</gallery>\n\n==Condition==\nIn July 2010 the piece underwent restoration to remove a green [[patina]] that formed on the sculpture. Perry's vision was for the piece to remain black. The piece was removed from its location to the west end of the building where it underwent its conservation by a contractor. The granite base that holds the 7,000 pound sculpture was also repaired.<ref name=\"JulyRepair\">{{cite web | author= | year=2010 | title=Continuum Sculpture Undergoes Restoration | work=AROUND NASM | publisher=National Air and Space Museum | url=http://archive.constantcontact.com/fs063/1101752115970/archive/1103512483603.html | accessdate= 3 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ad Astra (Lippold sculpture)|''Ad Astra'' (Lippold sculpture)]]\n*''[[Delta Solar]]''\n* [[List of public art in Washington, D.C., Ward 2]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://dcmemorials.com/index_indiv0000494.htm ''Continuum'' on dcMemorials]\n*[http://mathtourist.blogspot.com/2010/05/mobius-continuum.html The Mathematical Tourist on ''Continuum'']\n*[http://www.maa.org/mathland/mathtrek_9_4_00.html M\u00f6bius at Fermilab]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110429204301/http://www.si.edu/Exhibitions/Details/Outdoor-Sculptures-Air-and-Space-Museum-173 Outdoor Sculptures: Air and Space Museum]\n\n{{Mathematical art}}\n{{Public art in Washington, D.C.}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Continuum (Sculpture)}}\n[[Category:Mathematical artworks]]\n[[Category:1976 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of the Smithsonian Institution]]\n[[Category:Abstract sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Southwest Federal Center]]\n\n\n\n{{Smithsonian-stub}}\n{{sculpture-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artwork\n| image_file = Smithsonian Air and Space.jpg\n| painting_alignment = Front\n| image_size         = 200px\n| title              = Continuum\n| alt                =\n| other_language_1   =\n| other_title_1      =\n| other_language_2   =\n| other_title_2      =\n| artist             = Charles O. Perry\n| year               = {{Start date|1976}}\n| type               = [[Bronze]]\n| height_metric      =\n| width_metric       =\n| length_metric      =\n| height_imperial    = 14\n| width_imperial     =\n| length_imperial    =\n| metric_unit        = m\n| imperial_unit      = ft\n| city               = [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]]\n| museum             = [[National Air and Space Museum]]\n| coordinates        = {{coord|38|53|15.93|N|77|1|11.6|W|region:US}}\n| owner              = [[Smithsonian Institution]]\n}}\n\n'''''Continuum''''' is a public artwork by [[United States|American]] sculptor [[Charles O. Perry]]  located in front of the [[National Air and Space Museum]] in [[Washington, DC]], [[United States]].<ref name=\"Continuum\">{{cite web | author=Smithsonian | year=1993 | title=Continuum, (sculpture). | work=Save Outdoor Sculpture | publisher=Smithsonian | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!6509~!0#focus | accessdate= 2 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n\nThe sculpture is a large swirling abstract that consists of 8 bronze pieces painted black and placed on a pole. It moves freely.<ref name=\"Continuum\"/>\n\n==Information==\nAccording to the artist the piece \"began as an exploration of the [[M\u00f6bius strip]], a product of pure mathematics formed by joining two ends of a strip of paper after giving one end a 180 degree twist, thus creating only one edge. The center of the bronze sculpture symbolizes a [[black hole]], while the edge shows the flow of matter through the center from positive to negative space and back again in a [[continuum (theory)|continuum]].\"<ref name=\"CharlesOPerry\">{{cite web | author=Charles O. Perry | year= | title=Biography | work= | publisher=Charles Perry | url=http://www.charlesperry.com/Bio.html | accessdate= 2 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nA similar sculpture by Perry, ''Continuum II'', is installed in [[Marina Square]] in [[Singapore]] and dates to 1986.<ref name=\"Continuum II\">{{cite web | title=Continuum II | work=Singapore Public Art | publisher=Singapore Public Art | url=http://www.publicart.sg/?q=Charles-O-Perry_Continuum-II | accessdate=2 January 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619070004/http://www.publicart.sg/?q=Charles-O-Perry_Continuum-II | archive-date=19 June 2010 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n<gallery mode=packed heights=200>\nFile:Continuum from below.JPG|from below\nFile:Continuum from front (S).JPG|from the front (S)\nFile:Continuum from back (N) 05.JPG|from the side (SW)\nFile:Continuum from NW.JPG|from the side (NW)\nFile:Continuum from back (N).JPG|from the back (N)\nFile:Continuum Conservation.jpg|undergoing conservation in 2010\n</gallery>\n\n==Condition==\nIn July 2010 the piece underwent restoration to remove a green [[patina]] that formed on the sculpture. Perry's vision was for the piece to remain black. The piece was removed from its location to the west end of the building where it underwent its conservation by a contractor. The granite base that holds the 7,000 pound sculpture was also repaired.<ref name=\"JulyRepair\">{{cite web | author= | year=2010 | title=Continuum Sculpture Undergoes Restoration | work=AROUND NASM | publisher=National Air and Space Museum | url=http://archive.constantcontact.com/fs063/1101752115970/archive/1103512483603.html | accessdate= 3 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ad Astra (Lippold sculpture)|''Ad Astra'' (Lippold sculpture)]]\n*''[[Delta Solar]]''\n* [[List of public art in Washington, D.C., Ward 2]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://dcmemorials.com/index_indiv0000494.htm ''Continuum'' on dcMemorials]\n*[http://mathtourist.blogspot.com/2010/05/mobius-continuum.html The Mathematical Tourist on ''Continuum'']\n*[http://www.maa.org/mathland/mathtrek_9_4_00.html M\u00f6bius at Fermilab]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110429204301/http://www.si.edu/Exhibitions/Details/Outdoor-Sculptures-Air-and-Space-Museum-173 Outdoor Sculptures: Air and Space Museum]\n\n{{Mathematical art|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Continuum (Sculpture)}}\n[[Category:Mathematical artworks]]\n[[Category:1976 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of the Smithsonian Institution]]\n[[Category:Abstract sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Southwest Federal Center]]\n\n\n\n{{Smithsonian-stub}}\n{{sculpture-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ham II", "label": "safe", "comment":