lorence]]\n[[Category:Apothecaries]]\n", "name_user": "Errantius", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dante_Alighieri"}
{"title_page": "Russ Smith (basketball)", "text_new": "{{short description|American basketball player}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Chunky Russ Smith\n| image = Russ Smith (basketball) 2013.jpg\n| caption = Smith in 2013\n| position = [[Point guard]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 0\n| weight_lb = 166\n| league =  [[National Basketball League (China)|NBL]]\n| team = Guizhou White Tigers\n| number = 4\n| nationality  = American\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1991|4|19}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City|New York City, New York]]\n| high_school = \n*[[Archbishop Molloy High School|Archbishop Molloy]]<br>([[Queens, New York]])\n*[[South Kent School]]<br>([[South Kent, Connecticut]])\n| college = [[Louisville Cardinals men's basketball|Louisville]] (2010\u20132014)\n| draft_year = 2014\n| draft_round = 2\n| draft_pick = 47\n| draft_team = [[Philadelphia 76ers]]\n| career_start = 2014\n| years1 = {{nbay|2014|full=y}}\n| team1 = [[New Orleans Pelicans]]\n| years2 = 2014\u20132015\n| team2 = \u2192[[Fort Wayne Mad Ants]]\n| years3 = 2015\n| team3 = [[Memphis Grizzlies]]\n| years4 = 2015\n| team4 = \u2192[[Iowa Energy]]  \n| years5 = 2016\n| team5 = [[Delaware 87ers]]  \n| years6 = 2016\n| team6 = [[Galatasaray S.K. (men's basketball)|Galatasaray Odeabank]]\n| years7 = 2017\n| team7 = Delaware 87ers\n| years8 = 2017\n| team8 = [[Luoyang Zhonghe]]\n| years9 = 2017\u20132018\n| team9 = [[Fujian Sturgeons]]\n| years10 = 2018\n| team10 = Luoyang Zhonghe\n| years11 = 2018-2019\n| team11 = Fujian Sturgeons\n| years12 = 2019-present\n| team12 = [[Guizhou White Tigers]]\n| highlights =\n* [[National Basketball League (China)|NBL-China]] Player of the Year (2017)\n* [[National Basketball League (China)|NBL-China]] Guard of the Year (2017)\n* [[National Basketball League (China)|NBL-China]] Import of the Year (2017)\n* [[List of NCAA Men's Division I Basketball champions|NCAA champion]] ([[2013 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|2013]])*\n* Consensus first-team [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] ([[2014 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|2014]])\n* Third-team [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] - [[Sporting News|SN]], [[National Association of Basketball Coaches|NABC]] ([[2013 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|2013]])\n* First-team All-[[American Athletic Conference|AAC]] (2014)\n* USBWA All-District IV Player of the Year (2014)\n* First-team All-[[Big East Conference|Big East]] (2013)\n* [[Frances Pomeroy Naismith Award]] (2014)\n*[[American Athletic Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|AAC Tournament]] MVP ([[2014 American Athletic Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|2014]])\n<center>*''Later vacated''</center>\n| bbr = smithru01\n}}\n'''Russ Anton Smith''' (born April 19, 1991) is an American professional [[basketball]] player for the [[Guizhou White Tigers]] of the [[National Basketball League (China)|National Basketball League]] (NBL). He played [[college basketball]] for the [[Louisville Cardinals men's basketball|Louisville Cardinals]], playing a starring role as a junior in helping them win the 2013 NCAA championship, while earning third-team [[All-American]] by the [[National Association of Basketball Coaches|NABC]] and the [[Sporting News]].<ref> name=\"NABC AllAmerica\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gocards.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/032813aaa.html|title=Men's Basketball's Smith Earns NABC All-America Honors|publisher=GoCards.com|date=March 28, 2013|accessdate=April 9, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131215043152/http://www.gocards.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/032813aaa.html|archivedate=December 15, 2013}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|title=Russ Smith named Sporting News All-American|url=http://www.whas11.com/sports/Russ-Smith-named-Sporting-News-All-American-197233781.html |work=WHAS11.com |date=March 11, 2013 |accessdate=March 11, 2013 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006093419/http://www.whas11.com/sports/Russ-Smith-named-Sporting-News-All-American-197233781.html |archivedate=October 6, 2014 }}</ref> As a senior at Louisville, he was named a consensus first-team All-American.\n\n==High school career==\nSmith was born in [[New York City]] at NY Presbyterian Hospital to Paulette A. O'Neal and Russell Smith.  He went to [[Archbishop Molloy High School]] in Queens, N.Y. and played basketball for head coach [[Jack Curran]]. He led the New York City Catholic league ([[Catholic High School Athletic Association|CHSAA]]) in scoring as a junior averaging 24.5 points a game and as a senior averaging 29.6 points,<ref name=\"11 Russdiculous facts\">{{cite web|last=Winn |first=Luke |title=11 Russdiculous facts about Louisville's Russ Smith |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/college-basketball/news/20121221/russ-smith-louisville/ |work=SportsIllustrated.cnn.com |publisher=Sports Illustrated |date=December 21, 2012 |accessdate=April 1, 2013 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140325190324/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/college-basketball/news/20121221/russ-smith-louisville/ |archivedate=March 25, 2014 }}</ref> he also had a 7.3 rebound and 3.2 assist average his final season for the Molloy Stanners. His career high in points was 47, which he reached twice as a senior against St. Francis Prep and Christ the King. Smith was named to the 2009 New York State Sportswriters Association all-state team, made the first-team all-CHSAA \"AA\", and New York Daily News All-Queens first team as a senior. He played in the 2009 [[Jordan Brand Classic]] Regional Game at Madision Square Garden on April 18. Where he scored 27 points and earned co-MVP honors as his City team beat the Suburban team 129\u2013120. Russ played prep school basketball at [[South Kent School]] in 2010 averaging 19.7 points and 3.9 assists a game as South Kent went 20\u201312 on the season.<ref name=\"Russ Smith Bio\">{{cite web|title=Russ Smith Bio|url=http://www.gocards.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=357|work=GoCards.com|publisher=Louisville Cardinals|accessdate=March 31, 2013}}</ref>\n\n{{College Athlete Recruit Start|40=no|collapse=no|year=2010}}\n{{College Athlete Recruit Entry\n| recruit  = Russ Smith\n| position = G\n| hometown = Brooklyn,  NY\n| highschool = Archbishop Molloy High School, NY<br />South Kent School, CT\n| feet   = 6\n| inches = 0\n| weight = 165\n| 40     = \n| commitdate = 11/15/2009\n| scout stars  = 2\n| rivals stars = 3\n| espn grade = 88\n}}\n|}\n\n==College career==\n\n===Recruitment===\nLouisville overlooked Smith at first. Assistant coaches [[Ralph Willard]] and [[Steve Masiello]] were on a recruiting trip in South Kent in September 2009, looking at another player. They saw Smith, who they thought would be perfect for their system. Masiello had also known Smith's father since he was 15. Louisville started looking at Smith seriously, and Smith liked Louisville so much that he tried to commit before he had a scholarship offer.<ref name=\"11 Russdiculous facts\"/> Houston, LaSalle, Baylor and Arizona showed interest before he signed with the Cardinals.\n\n===Freshman year===\nUpon coming to school, Smith chose uniform #2.  Injuries limited Smith's playing time as a freshman. He had a broken foot, concussion, strained foot, and sore knee during the season and only saw action in 17 games.<ref name=\"Russ Smith Bio\"/> Smith was so miserable with the injuries and lack of playing time he decided to leave Louisville and go back home. He had even called his mom and told her he was coming home. But that day against West Virginia, coach Pitino put him in and told him to play hard. He had 3 points, 2 rebounds, one steal, and played good defense in his nine minutes of action.<ref name=\"LouisvilleWestVirginia\">{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=310260097|title=Peyton Siva's layup helps Louisville tip West Virginia|publisher=ESPN.com|date=January 26, 2011|accessdate=April 9, 2013}}</ref> Helping spark the Cardinals' comeback from down 11 to win by 1, when [[Peyton Siva]] hit a layup at the buzzer.<ref name=\"LouisvilleWestVirginia\" /> After that, he decided to stay. The Cardinals reached the championship game of the [[2011 Big East Men's Basketball Tournament]] but lost to [[2010\u201311 Connecticut Huskies men's basketball team|Connecticut]].<ref name=\"University of Louisville\">{{cite web|title=2011\u201312 Louisville Basketball Media Guide|url=http://www.guide.provations.com/louisville/2011mensbasketball#pg64|work=Player Bio: Peyton Siva|publisher=University of Louisville|accessdate=January 29, 2012}}</ref> Louisville  finished the season 25\u201310, 12\u20136 in the [[2010\u201311 Big East Conference men's basketball season|2010\u201311 Big East season]] tied for 3rd in the conference. They received an at-large bid and a #4 seed in the [[2011 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|2011 NCAA Tournament]] where they were upset in the second round by #13 seeded [[2010\u201311 Morehead State Eagles men's basketball team|Morehead State]] 61\u201362.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=310760097|title=Demonte Harper's 3-pointer with seconds left lifts Morehead State past Louisville|publisher=ESPN.com|date=March 18, 2011|accessdate=April 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Sophomore year===\nDuring his sophomore year in [[2011-12 Louisville Cardinals men's basketball team|2011\u201312]], Smith provided a spark off the bench. He was second in scoring despite being sixth in mins played for the Cardinals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/team/stats/_/id/97/year/2012/louisville-cardinals|title=Louisville Cardinals 2011\u201312 Statistics \u2013 Team and Player Stats \u2013 Men's College Basketball \u2013 ESPN|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=April 9, 2013}}</ref> In January 2012 he earned the nickname \"Russdiculous\" given to him by head coach [[Rick Pitino]], who has named a race horse \"Russdiculous\" also.<ref>{{cite web|first=Luke |last=Winn |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1206631/1/index.htm |title=Put Your Trust In ... Russ? |publisher=SportsIllustrated.cnn.com |date=December 24, 2012 |accessdate=April 9, 2013 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130131050850/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1206631/1/index.htm |archivedate=January 31, 2013 }}</ref> Smith set a school record for steals in a season with 87 steals in his 39 games played.<ref name=\"Russ Smith Bio\"/> Louisville won four games in four nights to win the [[2012 Big East Men's Basketball Tournament|2012 Big East tournament Championship]]. The Cardinals advanced to the Final Four of the [[2012 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|2012 NCAA Tournament]], upsetting #1 seed [[2011\u201312 Michigan State Spartans men's basketball team|Michigan State]] 57\u201344 in the sweet sixteen and defeating #7 seed [[2011\u201312 Florida Gators men's basketball team|Florida]] in the regional final, where Smith led Louisville with 19 points in the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=320840097|title=Louisville ends game on 23-8 run to stun Florida, reach Final Four|publisher=ESPN.com|date=March 24, 2012|accessdate=April 9, 2013}}</ref> Before losing in the national semifinals to [[Kentucky\u2013Louisville rivalry|arch-rival]] and eventual national champion [[2011\u201312 Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball team|Kentucky]]. Smith averaged 11.5 points, 2.5 rebounds, 1.9 assists, and 2.2 steals a game for the Cardinals, who finished the season with a 30\u201310 record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/player/gamelog/_/id/51478/year/2012/russ-smith |title=Russ Smith Stats, News, Videos, Highlights, Pictures, Bio \u2013 Louisville Cardinals \u2013 ESPN |publisher=ESPN.go.com|accessdate=April 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Junior year===\n[[File:Russ Smith Peyton Siva championship trophy.jpg|thumb|right|Smith (left) and [[Peyton Siva]] (right) with the [[2013 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament]] trophy.]]\nBefore the start of the [[2012\u201313 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2012\u201313 basketball season]] the [[2012\u201313 Louisville Cardinals men's basketball team|Louisville Cardinals men's basketball team]] was picked to finish 1st in the [[2012\u201313 Big East Conference men's basketball season|Big East Conference]] in polls done by Big East writers <ref>{{cite web|first=Mike|last=Waters|url=http://www.syracuse.com/orangebasketball/index.ssf/2012/10/louisville_tops_big_east_write.html|title=Louisville tops Big East writers' poll; Cardinals dominate all-league teams|publisher=Syracuse.com|date=October 16, 2012|accessdate=April 9, 2013}}</ref> and coaches.<ref>{{cite web|last=Smith|first=Jared|url=http://newyork.sbnation.com/2012/10/17/3517762/big-east-basketball-media-day-2012-coaches-poll-all-big-east-preseason|title=Big East basketball media day: Coaches' poll, All-Big East preseason teams and news|publisher=Newyork.sbnation.com|date=October 17, 2012|accessdate=April 9, 2013}}</ref> Louisville finished the regular season with a 26\u20135 record and 14\u20134 in the Big East to tie for a share of the Big East regular season championship with [[2012\u201313 Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team|Georgetown]] and [[2012\u201313 Marquette Golden Eagles men's basketball team|Marquette]], who also finished with a 14\u20134 conference record.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ennis|first=Mark|url=https://www.sbnation.com/college-basketball/2013/3/12/4091940/2013-big-east-tournament-preview-louisville-georgetown-syracuse-otto-porter |title=2013 Big East Tournament preview: Louisville and Georgetown favorites in league's swan song|publisher=SBNation.com|date=March 12, 2013|accessdate=April 9, 2013}}</ref>  Smith learned about the death of his high school coach Jack Curran before the start of the [[2013 Big East Men's Basketball Tournament|2013 Big East Tournament]]. Louisville played [[2012\u201313 Villanova Wildcats men's basketball team|Villanova]] in their first game of the tournament, Smith scored 28 points and said \"Today was definitely Coach Curran Day for me, and it will be the rest of my life\" in postgame interview that aired live on [[ESPN]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=330730097|title=Russ Smith leads Louisville over Villanova, into Big East semifinals|publisher=ESPN.com |date=March 15, 2013|accessdate=April 9, 2013}}</ref> Russ was named to the Big East All-Tournament Team<ref>{{cite web|last=Mike|first=Waters|title=Louisville's Peyton Siva joins Georgetown's Patrick Ewing as the only two-time winners of the Big East Most Outstanding Player award|url=http://www.syracuse.com/orangebasketball/index.ssf/2013/03/louisvilles_peyton_siva_joins.html|work=Syracuse.com|publisher=Syracuse Post-Standard|accessdate=March 17, 2013}}</ref> and his team won the Big East Tournament Championship game versus  [[2012-13 Syracuse Orange men's basketball team|Syracuse]] by a score of 78\u201361 after trailing by 13 at halftime.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=330750097|title=Louisville rallies from 16 down to win 2nd straight Big East title|publisher=ESPN.com|date=March 17, 2013|accessdate=April 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nLouisville, with a 29\u20135 record, was selected the #1 overall seed for the [[2013 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|2013 NCAA Tournament]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/9063277/2013-ncaa-tournament-louisville-cardinals-named-top-overall-seed|title=Louisville claims top overall seed|publisher=ESPN.com|date=March 26, 2013|accessdate=April 9, 2013}}</ref> In his first two games of the NCAA tournament at [[Rupp Arena]] he had 23 points verses [[2012\u201313 North Carolina A&T Aggies men's basketball team|North Carolina A&T]] and had 27 against [[2012\u201313 Colorado State Rams men's basketball team|Colorado State]]. Louisville fans liked what Smith was doing on the floor so much they started chanting RussArena<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=330820097|title=Louisville routs Colorado State behind Russ Smith's 27 points|publisher=ESPN.com|date=March 23, 2013|accessdate=April 9, 2013}}</ref> near the end of the Colorado State game and made a Twitter hashtag #RussArena.<ref>{{cite web|first=Tommy|last=Tomlinson|url=http://www.sportsonearth.com/article/43306768/|title=Russ Smith could be the key to Louisville's Final Four run. &#124; SportsonEarth.com : Tommy Tomlinson Article |publisher=SportsonEarth.com|date=March 26, 2013|accessdate=April 9, 2013}}</ref> He tied his career high of 31 points and the Cardinals beat the [[2012-13 Oregon Ducks men's basketball team|Oregon Ducks]] 77\u201369 in the Sweet Sixteen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=330880097|title=Russ Smith scores 31 points to boost Louisville into Elite 8|publisher=ESPN.com|date=March 30, 2013|accessdate=April 9, 2013}}</ref> In Louisville's 85\u201363 regional final win against [[2012-13 Duke Blue Devils men's basketball team|Duke]], Smith recorded 23 points and was subsequently named the Most Outstanding Player of the tournament's Midwest Region. During the Duke game Smith witnessed [[Kevin Ware]] suffer a horrible broken leg accident that left the team very emotional. Ware said \"Just go win this game for me. Just go win this game. Don't worry about me, I'm fine.\" while being attended to by medical staff who was preparing him for a trip to the hospital. Louisville outscored Duke 64 to 43 after the Ware injury and credited Ware's positive attitude about his injury for their win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=330900097|title=Emotional Louisville overcomes injury to Kevin Ware to reach Final Four|publisher=ESPN.go.com|date=April 1, 2013|accessdate=April 1, 2013}}</ref> In Louisville's next game Smith had 21 points in a 72\u201368 win over [[2012\u201313 Wichita State Shockers men's basketball team|Wichita State]] in the Final Four.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=330960097|title=Louisville edges upstart Wichita State, advances to NCAA title game|publisher=ESPN.go.com|date=April 7, 2013|accessdate=April 9, 2013}}</ref> Smith averaged 18.7 points, 3.3 rebounds, 2.9 assists and 2.1 steals this season for the Cardinals who won the national championship over Michigan with a 35\u20135 record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/player/_/id/51478/russ-smith |title=Russ Smith Stats, News, Videos, Highlights, Pictures, Bio \u2013 Louisville Cardinals \u2013 ESPN |publisher=ESPN.go.com |accessdate=April 9, 2013 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329072925/http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/player/_/id/51478/russ-smith |archivedate=March 29, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Senior year===\nOn April 24, 2013, Smith announced he would stay at Louisville for his senior year in an attempt to improve his draft stock the upcoming year.<ref>{{cite web|first=Morty|last=Ain|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/9893546/louisville-guard-russ-smith-why-returning-senior-season-espn-magazine|title=The return of Russdiculous|publisher=ESPN.com|date=November 1, 2013|accessdate=November 1, 2013}}</ref> On February 28, he was named one of the 10 semi-finalists for [[Naismith College Player of the Year]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Top 10 National Semifinalists Named for 2014 Men's Naismith Trophy presented by AT&T |url=http://naismithawards.com/PressBox/ArticleView/tabid/209/ArticleId/12/2014-Mens-Naismith-Trophy-presented-by-AT-T-Top-10-National-Semifinalists.aspx |work=Naismith Awards |accessdate=February 18, 2014 |date=February 28, 2014 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006124015/http://naismithawards.com/PressBox/ArticleView/tabid/209/ArticleId/12/2014-Mens-Naismith-Trophy-presented-by-AT-T-Top-10-National-Semifinalists.aspx |archivedate=October 6, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nLouisville finished the season with a 31-6 record, earning a 4 seed in the tournament. Louisville opened against [[2013\u201314 Manhattan Jaspers basketball team|Manhattan]] in the second round, Smith led the game in scoring with 18 points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=400546903|title=Louisville comes alive late to squeak past Manhattan|publisher=ESPN.com|date=March 21, 2014|accessdate=March 21, 2014}}</ref> After Manhattan, Louisville advanced 66-51 against [[2013\u201314 Saint Louis Billikens men's basketball team|Saint Louis]]. Smith tallied up 11 points and tied for the most assists with 7.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=400548508|title=Louisville tops Saint Louis, reaches Sweet 16 for 3rd straight year|publisher=ESPN.com|date=March 22, 2014|accessdate=March 22, 2014}}</ref> Smith ended his college career with 23 points in the Sweet Sixteen, losing against Kentucky.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=400548877|title=Kentucky uses late surge to boot defending champ Louisville|publisher=ESPN.com|date=March 29, 2014|accessdate=March 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\nSmith was selected on the Associated Press First Team All American list.<ref>{{cite web|first=Jonathan|last=Lintner|url=http://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/college/louisville/2014/03/31/russ-smith-makes-ap-american-team/7117111/|title=Russ Smith makes two All-America teams|publisher=Courier-Journal.com|date=March 31, 2014|accessdate=March 31, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===College honors===\n*2013 NCAA Midwest Regional Most Outstanding Player\n*2013 Big East All-Tournament Team<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigeast.org/News/tabid/435/Article/242937/louisville-wins-2013-big-east-mens-basketball-championship.aspx |title=Louisville Wins 2013 BIG EAST Men's Basketball Championship > The BIG EAST Conference > News |publisher=Bigeast.org |date=March 16, 2013 |accessdate=April 9, 2013 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511034042/http://www.bigeast.org/News/tabid/435/Article/242937/louisville-wins-2013-big-east-mens-basketball-championship.aspx |archivedate=May 11, 2013 }}</ref>\n*2013 Big East All-Conference First Team<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collegesportsmadness.com/article/6010 |title=Big East Men's Basketball 2012\u20132013 All-Conference Teams |publisher=College Sports Madness |date= |accessdate=April 9, 2013}}</ref>\n*2013 Lute Olson All-America Team<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gocards.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/032513aae.html |title=Men's Basketball's Smith Named to Lute Olson All-America Team \u2013 Louisville Cardinals Official Athletic Site |publisher=Gocards.com |date=March 25, 2013|accessdate=April 9, 2013}}</ref>\n*2013 Sporting News All-American Third Team\n*2013 NABC All-America Third Team\n*2013 College Sports Madness All-America First Team<ref name=\"NABC AllAmerica\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gocards.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/032813aaa.html|title=Men's Basketball's Smith Earns NABC All-America Honors|publisher=GoCards.com|date=March 28, 2013|accessdate=April 9, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131215043152/http://www.gocards.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/032813aaa.html|archivedate=December 15, 2013}}</ref>\n*2014 John Wooden Award All-American team<ref>{{cite web|first=Myron|last=Medcalf|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/10702458/doug-mcdermott-shabazz-napier-anchor-wooden-award-all-american-team|title=Wooden All-American team revealed|work=ESPN.com|date=May 31, 2014|accessdate=May 31, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===New Orleans Pelicans (2014\u20132015)===\nOn June 26, 2014, Smith was selected with the 47th overall pick in the [[2014 NBA draft]] by the [[Philadelphia 76ers]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Scott|last=Polacek|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2067869-russ-smith-drafted-by-76ers-latest-news-reaction-and-analysis|title=Russ Smith Drafted by 76ers: Latest News, Reaction and Analysis|work=BleacherReport.com|date=June 26, 2014|accessdate=June 26, 2014}}</ref> The next day, his rights were traded to the [[New Orleans Pelicans]] in exchange for the rights to [[Pierre Jackson]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nba.com/sixers/news/140627-pierre-jackson|title=Sixers Acquire Rights To Point Guard Pierre Jackson|work=NBA.com|date=June 27, 2014|accessdate=June 28, 2014}}</ref> Following the draft, Smith noted his frustration in some draft analysts questioning his efficiency. He was frustrated by teams waffling over his ability to play point guard at the NBA level, and was frustrated that several unnamed big-time NBA draft prospects avoided workouts with him in the two-month build-up to the draft.<ref>{{cite web|first=Jeff|last=Greer|title=Russ Smith frustrated by NBA draft, ready to start|url=http://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/college/louisville/2014/06/26/louisvilles-russ-smith-selected-xxx-xx-pick-nba-draft/11411759/|work=Courier-Journal.com|date=January 7, 2015|accessdate=February 8, 2016}}</ref> He later signed his rookie scale contract with the Pelicans on July 15.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/pelicans/news/pelicans-sign-russ-smith|title=Pelicans Sign Russ Smith|work=NBA.com|date=July 15, 2014|accessdate=July 15, 2014}}</ref> During his rookie season with the Pelicans, he had multiple assignments with the [[Fort Wayne Mad Ants]] of the [[NBA Development League]].<ref name=assign>{{cite news|title=All-Time NBA Assignments|url=http://dleague.nba.com/all-time-nba-assignments/|accessdate=December 17, 2015|work=NBA.com}}</ref>\n\n===Memphis Grizzlies (2015)===\nOn January 12, 2015, Smith was traded to the [[Memphis Grizzlies]] in a three-team deal involving the Pelicans and the [[Boston Celtics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/grizzlies/news/grizzlies-acquire-green-smith-three-team-trade-150112|title=Memphis Grizzlies acquire Jeff Green and Russ Smith in three-team trade with Boston Celtics and New Orleans Pelicans|work=NBA.com|date=January 12, 2015|accessdate=January 12, 2015}}</ref> He was assigned multiple times to the [[Iowa Energy]] in his rookie season.<ref name=\"assign\" /> Smith made his playoff debut on May 3, 2015, in a 101\u201386 loss to the [[Golden State Warriors]] in the Western Conference semi-finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20150503/MEMGSW/gameinfo.html|title=Warriors roll past Grizzlies 101-86 in Game 1 of West semis|work=NBA.com|date=May 3, 2015|accessdate=May 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn December 17, 2015, Smith was reassigned to the Iowa Energy,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/grizzlies/news/grizzlies-assign-ennis-martin-smith-iowa-energy-151217|title=Grizzlies assign James Ennis, Jarrell Martin and Russ Smith to Iowa Energy|work=NBA.com|date=December 17, 2015|accessdate=December 17, 2015}}</ref> but was recalled later that day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/?id=5081258|title=Memphis Grizzlies Recall James Ennis, Jarell Martin and Russ Smith from Iowa Energy|work=OurSportsCentral.com|date=December 17, 2015|accessdate=December 17, 2015}}</ref> He was reassigned again on December 22,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/grizzlies/news/ennis-martin-smith-to-iowa-151222|title=Grizzlies re-assign James Ennis, Jarell Martin and Russ Smith to Iowa Energy|work=NBA.com|date=December 22, 2015|accessdate=December 22, 2015}}</ref> and recalled two days later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/?id=5083117|title=Memphis Grizzlies Recall James Ennis, Jarell Martin and Russ Smith from the Iowa Energy|work=OurSportsCentral.com|date=December 24, 2015|accessdate=December 24, 2015}}</ref> On December 29, he was waived by the Grizzlies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/grizzlies/news/grizz-sign-hollins-151229|title=Memphis Grizzlies sign center Ryan Hollins|date=December 29, 2015|work=NBA.com|accessdate=December 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Delaware 87ers (2016)===\nOn January 13, 2016, Smith was acquired by the [[Delaware 87ers]] of the [[NBA Development League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://delaware.dleague.nba.com/news/delaware-87ers-acquire-russ-smith/|title=Delaware 87ers acquire Russ Smith|date=January 13, 2016|work=NBA.com|accessdate=January 13, 2016}}</ref> Two days later, he made his debut for the 87ers in a 119\u2013104 win over [[Raptors 905]], scoring a team-high 37 points in 28 minutes of action off the bench.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dleague.nba.com/games/20160115/RAPDEL/|title=87ers Run Past Raptors|date=January 15, 2016|work=NBA.com|accessdate=January 16, 2016}}</ref> On February 1, 2016, he was named NBA D-League Performer of the Week for games played Monday, January 25 through Sunday, January 31. The honor was the first of Smith's career. He helped Delaware to a 2\u20131 week, averaging 28.7 points (fifth in the league) on 48 percent shooting (28-for-58) to go with a league-leading 8.7 assists, 4.3 rebounds and 2.0 steals.<ref>{{cite web|title=87ers Guard Russ Smith Named NBA Development League Performer of the Week|url=http://dleague.nba.com/news/russ-smith-nba-development-league-performer-of-week-020116/|work=NBA.com|date=February 1, 2016|accessdate=February 8, 2016}}</ref> On March 18, he recorded his first career triple-double after recording 20 points, 13 rebounds and 16 assists in a 116-98 win over the Fort Wayne Mad Ants.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://stats.gleague.nba.com/game/2021500392/|title=Fort Wayne Mad Ants 98 - Delaware 87ers 116|publisher=G-League Stats|date=March 18, 2016|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref> On March 23, he set a D-League scoring record with 65 points on 24-of-42 shooting from the field in a 140\u2013129 loss to the [[Canton Charge]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Russdiculous! Top Prospect Russ Smith Pours in Record 65 Points for Delaware 87ers|url=http://dleague.nba.com/games/20160323/delctn/|work=NBA.com|date=March 23, 2016|accessdate=March 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Russ Smith Goes Off for NBA D-League Record 65 Points!|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3f39wzZBGaE|work=YouTube.com|date=March 23, 2016|accessdate=March 25, 2016}}</ref> On March 29, he was waived by the 87ers after being deemed to have a season-ending injury.<ref>{{cite web|title=NBA D-League Transactions |url=http://dleague.nba.com/transactions/ |work=NBA.com |accessdate=March 31, 2016 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401043327/http://dleague.nba.com/transactions/ |archivedate=April 1, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Europe (2016)===\nOn July 27, 2016, Smith signed a one-year contract with [[Galatasaray S.K. (men's basketball)|Galatasaray Odeabank]] of the [[Turkish Basketball Super League|Turkish BSL]] and [[EuroLeague]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportando.com/en/europe/turkey/207799/galatasaray-signs-russ-smith.html|title= Galatasaray signs Russ Smith|date=July 27, 2016|access-date=July 27, 2016|publisher=Sportando.com}}</ref> In December 2016, he parted ways with Galatasaray.<ref>{{cite news|title=Galatasaray parted ways with Russ Smith|url=http://www.eurohoops.net/featured/365740/galatasaray-parted-ways-russ-smith|accessdate=January 10, 2017|work=Eurohoops.net|date=December 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Return to the Delaware 87ers (2017)===\nOn January 20, 2017, Smith was re-acquired by the Delaware 87ers.<ref>[https://twitter.com/Sevens/status/822543651817607172 The #Sevens have reacquired G Russ Smith - #Sixers 2014 Draft pick set a team and league single-game scoring record with 65 pts on 3/23/16]</ref>\n\n===China (2017\u2013present)===\nOn June 3, 2017, Smith signed with Luoyang Zhonghe of China for the 2017 [[National Basketball League (China)|NBL]] season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Russ Smith signs in China with Luoyang where he averaged 60 points per game which is a world record.|url=http://www.sportando.com/en/world/asia/236057/russ-smith-signs-in-china-with-luoyang.html|accessdate=July 5, 2017|work=Sportando.com|date=June 3, 2017}}</ref> In his debut with Luoyang, Smith scored 62 points (including 7 3-pointers made) and recorded 3 steals in a 138-123 loss to the Anhui Lightning.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurobasket.com/boxScores/China/2017/0625_15107_21474.asp|title=Anhui 138 - Luoyang 123|publisher=EuroBasket|date=June 25, 2017|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>. On July 5, 2017, Smith scored a career-high 81 points to go along with 8 rebounds and 7 assists in a 142-130 win over the Henan Golden Elephants.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurobasket.com/boxScores/China/2017/0705_21474_9956.asp|title=Luoyang 142 - Henan 130|publisher=EuroBasket|date=July 5, 2017|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter that summer league's campaign wrapped up, he signed with the [[Fujian Sturgeons]] for the 2017-18 [[Chinese Basketball Association|CBA]] season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fujian Sturgeons sign Andrew Nicholson and Russ Smith |url=https://sportando.basketball/en/asia/china/285361/fujian-sturgeons-sign-andrew-nicholson-and-russ-smith.html |website=Sportando |accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref> <ref>https://hoopshype.com/2018/03/26/russ-smith-on-possible-nba-comeback-ascent-at-louisville-reaction-to-vacated-title-61-2-ppg-average-in-china-and-more/</ref> \n\n==Career Statistics==\n{{Basketball player statistics legend}}\n{{Basketball player statistics start}}\n|-\n| align=center | 2014-15\n| align=left | [[New Orleans Pelicans|New Orleans]] / [[Memphis Grizzlies|Memphis]]\n| [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n| 12 || 5.4 || .320 || .182 || '''.923''' || .5 || .7 || .3 || .0 || 2.5\n|-\n| align=center | 2014-15\n| align=left | [[Fort Wayne Mad Ants|Fort Wayne]] / [[Iowa Wolves|Iowa]] \n| [[NBA G-League|NBA G-League]]\n| 25 || 30.8 || .494 || '''.385''' || .688 || 4.3 || 4.2 || 1.9 || '''.2''' || 18.1\n|-\n| align=center | 2015-16\n| align=left | [[Memphis Grizzlies|Memphis]]\n| [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n| 15 || 4.4 || .318 || .200 || .615 || .6 || .7 || .3 || .1 || 1.5\n|-\n| align=center | 2015-16\n| al